(78, 1, '2012-10-29 19:59:25', '2012-10-29 19:59:25', '<h2>Assessing What Needs Improving:</h2>\r\nAs it stands, the <a title="Press" href="http://leeprecision.com/pro-1000-223.html">press</a> i''m using is beautifully engineered, and aside from maybe a .05% error percentage, works great! Wanting to improve things, I decided to implement an MCU-based solution to make it work a little better.\r\n\r\nFirst thing is first though, I''ll explain how to reload a cartridge with this press, so we can better understand where the problems are, and where things slow down.\r\n<h1>Reloading with the Pro 1000 101:</h1>\r\nFor this press, I reload a <a title=".223 Remington" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.223_Remington">.223 Remington</a> cartridge. This cartridge is what''s referred to as a ''necked'' cartridge,\r\n\r\n<img class="alignright" style="color: #333333; font-style: normal; font-weight: bold; line-height: 24px; border: 0px none #eeeeee; padding: 0px; text-align: center; margin: 5px auto 0px !important; -webkit-user-drag: none; display: block; max-width: 98%;" title="Necked Cartridge" src="http://images.bisonballistics.com/rifle_case_diagram.png" alt="A necked cartridge (taken from www.bisonballistics.com)" width="215" height="151" />which means that the cartridge has a taper from it''s base diameter to a smaller diameter that the projectile is pressed into. A key thing to consider with necked cartridges in comparison to ''straight'' cartridges is that every time the cartridge is fired, that restriction in diameter towards the top allows the case to stretch along it''s length. This deformation requires the use of a ''full resizing die'' to correct upon reloading. In  reloading press, a ''die'' is term for a uniform-diameter piece that accomplishes one, or many steps of the reloading process. So let''s see what the reloading process entails by first understand what a loaded cartridge consists of, and then understanding the steps to turn spent ammo into new ammo.\r\n<h2>Anatomy Of A Loaded Cartridge</h2>\r\nThe .223 (I''ll just use this as shorthand for .223 Remington) round is much like any round in composition. It consists of:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Casing: The metallic ''case'' which the powder and primer are held, and the bullet is pressed into to close.</li>\r\n	<li>Powder: Some variety of smokeless power that provides the primary ''oomph'' for the expansion of gas that propels the projectile out of the barrel.</li>\r\n	<li>Primer: The impact sensitive cap seated in the center rear of the bullet. When struck  hard by a pointed steel ''pin'', the primer detonates and ignites powder in the cartridge.</li>\r\n	<li>Projectile: More commonly: the bullet. Upon the rapid expansion of gas in the cartridge, the bullet dislodges from the cartridge and is forced down the barrel by the expanding gas.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Reloading the .223 / 5.56x45 NATO cartridge</h2>\r\n<strong>1-Acquire spent brass casings:</strong>\r\n\r\nAfter being fired, a casing may be reloaded. In general these cases must be brass, centerfire casings. Centerfire refers to cartridges that contain a replaceable ''primer'' that is set in the middle of the case''s rear.  Rimfire rounds such as .22LR cannot be reloaded, as the primer is integrated into the casing, and cannot be removed and replaced. After a certain amount of firing, especially with too ''hot'' of loads (Excessive amount of powder), a casing may develop pressure cracks. Such defects, also including severely dented casings, disqualifies them from reloading. With some exception towards nickle cases, brass casings are the only candidate for reloading due to the metal being more malleable at room temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>1(Optional)- Clean casings:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>Using a <a title="tumbler" href="http://www.midwayusa.com/product/587176/frankford-arsenal-quick-n-ez-case-tumbler-110-volt">tumbler</a> filled with corn/nut husks and polishing compound, dirty cases should be cleaned and polished. This process reduces the amount of dirt and grime that may get into your dies while reloading.\r\n\r\n<strong>2-Check casing length and trim if necessary:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>As I had mentioned, a necked case will expand every time it is fired. To combat this, I first measure the length of each cartridge with a caliper and toss aside any cartridge that exceeds the specification, which in this case would be 1.760 inches. When I amass enough of these, I trim them and toss them into the bin of cases that are ready to reload.\r\n\r\n<strong>3-Lubricate Cases:</strong>\r\n\r\nPutting a case through the resizing die involves a whole bunch of friction along the outside of the case, so we need to lubricate the outside of the cases thoroughly with a <a title="case lube" href="http://www.midwayusa.com/product/1165269233/hornady-one-shot-case-lube">case lube</a>.\r\n\r\n4-Manually load case into feed tubes:\r\n\r\nThe Pro 1000 contains 4 feed tubes that rotate to feed cases into the first stage of the press. Upon emptying one tube, the assembly is rotated to allow the next tube to drain while the depleted one is refilled.\r\n\r\n5-[First Stage]De-Prime and resize case:\r\n\r\nThe first stage of the press, at the topmost of it''s stroke, forces the case into the resizing and de-priming die. This die is precisely machined to conform the case to the correct dimensions, and has a steel pin going through the middle that at the same time pops the used primer out of it''s seat.\r\n\r\n5(Optional) Remove case and clean primer pocket:\r\n\r\nSome, or most recommend reaming out the pocket containing the primer to remove carbon deposits.\r\n\r\n<strong>6-[Second Stage] Re-prime and Fill cartridge with powder:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>After de-priming, the cartridge rotates to the next stage, and on the downward stroke is re-primed. On it''s upward stroke, It opens the powder gate, which empties a chamber containing a precise volume of powder. On the stroke lowering, this chamber is rotated back under the powder supply which is filled until the next time a cartridge trips the chamber to move forwards and dispense.\r\n\r\n7-[Third Stage] Press in projectile:\r\n\r\nSo we have new powder, a new primer, and we''re ready to seal everything in. In this case, the projectile is manually placed at the neck, and the upward stroke is started, the ''seating die'' presses this bullet into the case at a depth specified by it''s depth dial.\r\n\r\n8-Eject finished cartridge, check length:\r\n\r\nBy specification, the finished cartridge should be no longer than 2.26" long. For a semi-automatic rifle, I typically go for about 2.23-2.24". At times, the seating die may become misadjusted, so repeatedly checking this is always for the best.\r\n\r\n<strong>9-Put completed cases in box, feel productive.</strong>\r\n<h1>Now For the Issues:</h1>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li> [Stage 1]: The primers, after ejected, come out the bottom of the press, amassing in every undesirable nook and cranny of your workspace. A simple engineered solution to route these somewhere else would be cool.</li>\r\n	<li>[Stage 2]: If a new primer doesn''t feed or press correctly, powder will still be poured into the case. If this happens, the powder spills everywhere, not only again occupying every nook of the workspace, but also requiring the press to be taken apart and cleaned. If i could have a beep or something when the primer feeder uses a primer, that would be great.</li>\r\n	<li>[Stage 2]: It''s easy to forget about re-filling the powder reservoir. As a result, creating a bunch of powder-less cartridges is incredibly easy. Some means to alert me that it is low would be great!</li>\r\n	<li>Checking length manually is a pain. I''d love to have something that does this for me!</li>\r\n	<li>I don''t like touching the cases with my hands. Reason being that the oils in one''s skin rapidly accelerate tarnishing of the case. This results in less shinyness.. If i could make something to arrange them in a box for me, it would be cool.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Addressing these:</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Mounting the press on a mount that integrates a funnel directly under a press would allow me to route the primers to a tube of some sort, and into a box. I''ll cut a notch at the base of this funnel on the outside of the wood base, and after mounting some plate to close that off, put in a piece of pipe that takes primers coming from this notch, and knock them off to the side!</li>\r\n	<li>A simple LED and photoresistor(PR) combo may due. In the run loop of the MCU, constantly check this sensor for sharp variation, which would signal the light that would come through the small gap between primers. Beep once when this happens.</li>\r\n	<li>LED and PR! Just drill a hole in the base of the reservoir, put a LED at one end, and the PR on the other. When powder is obstructing the light, the reading will be x, when there is no powder to do so the reading is y. Check for y and light something up if it''s true!</li>\r\n	<li>A bit more technical. I would need to make an interruption in the flow from the press to the box. I could drop the cartridge horizontally in a pocket, have a wall of this pocket be attached to a motor and linear pot, and have that wall collapse until seizing  on top of the shell. At that point, the reading from the pot is interpreted into the length. If it is right, drop out the bottom of the pocket, allowing the case to continue. Else light something up so I''d know to grab the case and set it aside. I could route the shells depending on good/bad length, but after a bad length, I''ll just correct the die, so spending a few extra bucks and hours of time for functionality that will be used a fraction of the time is silly. I''m not made of money! The second idea here is to use light again. Drop the case into a light-less cavity with a LED/PR combo monitoring the area around the tip of the cartridge. Given uniformity in placement and projectile finish, there should be a different reading with a variation in length. A whole lot simpler than the motor/feedback pot to build, but a bit more out of the box.</li>\r\n	<li>Not difficult. The press drops completed shells down through a pipe. Having two stepper motors control an x-y plate allows me to shift a container to an empty spot under that pipe. By putting a momentary switch at the top of the stroke, I can signal the software controlling these servos to advance to the next available spot. Building a 2d array each containing boolean values, and creating functions to read and manipulate this in regards to the servo''s controls should be cake. Again, it''s poor-man''s engineering that makes this tough.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;', '', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '68-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-29 19:59:25', '2012-10-29 19:59:25', '', 68, 'http://www.oneseventyfour.com/?p=78', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(79, 1, '2012-10-29 20:28:41', '2012-10-29 20:28:41', 'Having a good history as a mechanic, I''ve always been tooling around with the mechanical aspect of cars, and as a result have a good handle on them. Upon getting more familiar with embedded systems, I looked more towards the increasingly prevalent use of computers in vehicle peripherals, and got excited about implementing my own centralized computer for integrating a variety of these computerized peripherals. What I wanted to incorporate in to this was:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A PC with full-featured OS, likely linux, with as quick of boot time possible.</li>\r\n	<li>An ARM MCU interfaced with said OS responsible for control of climate control, radio, CAN-BUS for connecting with the vechicle''s ECU, and eventually interfacing with cruise control to create a distance-based cruise control setting for use on open highway trips.</li>\r\n	<li>Some Software bridge connecting my Water/Methanol Injection system with the ECU, allowing more precise triggering promoting better highway mileage.</li>\r\n	<li>A PC application that turns this functionality into an easy to use experience using large buttons and text.</li>\r\n	<li>A touchscreen to present all of this to the driver.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt is certainly the most ambitious of my projects, but is something I am confident in once the financial end can be satisfied.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Introduction:Car PC', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'introductioncar-pc', '', '', '2012-10-30 20:51:16', '2012-10-30 20:51:16', '', 0, 'http://www.oneseventyfour.com/?p=79', 0, 'post', '', 0),
