(90, 1, '2012-10-29 21:39:04', '2012-10-29 21:39:04', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI wanted something fun out front that, while entertaining trick-or-treaters, didn''t actually endanger them... Certainly a difficult set of requirements. Thinking for a bit, I settled on fire... well colored fire inside of a pumpkin.\r\n\r\nFirst was making/gathering sawdust: Not difficult, just took an auto-planer and ran it over 2x4 studs. Sawdust ahoy!\r\n\r\nNext was the trickier part. I had decided on green flames, the chemical requisite of such is Copper Sulfate. Not wanting to go about hunting for chemicals/ buying anything, I looked around and found that I had some sulfuric acid and copper heatsinks. Bingo.\r\n\r\nHooking the heatsinks up to the anode and cathode of the 5v rail of a computer''s power supply, and grounding the PWR_ON pin on the PSU''s 24 pin, things got rolling. Now for anyone deciding to do this themselves, two things:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>We''re dealing with battery acid, essentially. Take care to wear gloves and pour gently. Because the acid is merely a electrolyte/conductor, it may be wise to dilute with distilled water (I just use tap...). Thankfully, it doesn''t fume as bad as muratic acid/ etc., so we''ve got that going for us.</li>\r\n	<li>Because of the chemical process going on, it''s wise to place your negative copper above the positive. This is because your negative will be emitting hydrogen, while the positive is where the copper sulfate is separating. If you don''t do this, your negative conductor will absorb a fair amount of your precious CuSO4!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAbout an hour will pass now, and you''ll notice an obvious blue tint at the bottom of your (hopefully) glass container. Disconnect power, and throw the solution in a pot. Boil off the water, and upon being fairly sure that it''s all sulfuric acid, filter it through something you don''t care about. Set it out in some light, let it dry up, and there you have it! Some off-blue stuff we call Copper Sulfate!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_85" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3957.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-85" title="Copper Sulfate" src="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3957-300x199.jpg" alt="Copper Sulfate" width="300" height="199" /></a> Copper Sulfate[/caption]\r\n\r\nBut we aren''t done yet... After all, we''ve got all of that sawdust. Take a soup can now, clean it out and set it aside. Take that can and put some copper sulfate and an equal volume of water in. Because I have a decent amount of methanol for my car lying around, I often substitute water for a 75/25 mix of Methanol/Water. The consistency should be of about a paste.\r\n\r\nGive a few hours for the sawdust to soak everything up and dry out a little, and put that can in a pumpkin. Light and enjoy a night of a green fire-filled pumpkin, or just green fire in general. Hopefully all goes well!', 'Today''s Fun: Preparing for Halloween', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '84-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-29 21:39:04', '2012-10-29 21:39:04', '', 84, 'http://www.oneseventyfour.com/?p=90', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
