(97, 1, '2012-10-29 20:28:41', '2012-10-29 20:28:41', 'Having a good history as a mechanic, I''ve always been tooling around with the mechanical aspect of cars, and as a result have a good handle on them. Upon getting more familiar with embedded systems, I looked more towards the increasingly prevalent use of computers in vehicle peripherals, and got excited about implementing my own centralized computer for integrating a variety of these computerized peripherals. What I wanted to incorporate in to this was:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A PC with full-featured OS, likely linux, with as quick of boot time possible.</li>\r\n	<li>An ARM MCU interfaced with said OS responsible for control of climate control, radio, CAN-BUS for connecting with the vechicle''s ECU, and eventually interfacing with cruise control to create a distance-based cruise control setting for use on open highway trips.</li>\r\n	<li>A PC application that turns this functionality into an easy to use experience using large buttons and text.</li>\r\n	<li>A touchscreen to present all of this to the driver.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt is certainly the most ambitious of my projects, but is something I am confident in once the financial end can be satisfied.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Introduction:Car PC', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '79-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-29 20:28:41', '2012-10-29 20:28:41', '', 79, 'http://www.oneseventyfour.com/?p=97', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(98, 1, '2012-10-31 07:08:34', '2012-10-31 07:08:34', 'The car, upon the start of the  project, had a Water/Methanol Injection system that I had put in earlier, but had yet to actually start using. In anticipation of eventually starting this project, I had to open up the system''s controller and break out signal wires going behind the dash. As it would entail, most of the car''s exterior had to be removed, and I had taken that opportunity to put in more sound dampening material. Now Dynamat, Hushmat or any application-specific acousic matting is INSANELY expensive, needing about 1-2 hundred bucks for a good application. I''m not a fan of that, so I went over to Lowes and picked up literally an identical thing, for about 1/4 the cost. Budget-stricken audiophiles know it well by it''s name, Peel and Seel(sic). Apart from a slightly thinner aluminum backing, P&amp;S is identical to application, and by the sound of it, quality to the products actually intended to be used in cars.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_100" align="aligncenter" width="300"]<a href="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3700.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-100" title="WRX Backend Stripped" src="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3700-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a> Looking towards the back: Didn''t take the top panel completely off as I didn''t want to remove the seatbelt roll assembly.[/caption]\r\n\r\nMore useful to the layperson in cars, sound dampening is more generally used in luxury vehicles. This is part of what quiets a freeway roar of an 80''s honda down to a quiet whisper that a newer Mercedes may have. Either way you look at it, It''s a great way to spend money on your car, and an even better one to do a REALLY deep cleaning of it.\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_99" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3698.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-99" title="WRX Partially Stripped" src="http://www.oneseventyfour.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/DSC_3698-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a> Stripped out seats, floor panels with sound dampening applied.[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo after the unnecessary step of sound dampening, it was time do do what I actually intended. A water/methanol injection system holds two primary immediate benefits, and what I call a long term benefit. The first of the immediate benefits is that introducing methanol to the fuel/air mixture  increases the octane of that mixture immediately. Now before we go off disallusioned that higher octane fuel is inherently more powerful, let me tell you that it isn''t, and here''s why. Octane, simply put, is an assessment of a gasoline''s "Knock resistance". What is knock? Well that''s a long blurb, but in  a nutshell, it involves the fuel/air mixture being ignited in the cylinder in an excessively catastrophic manner. Isn''t that what''s supposed to happen? No! Once ignited by the spark plug, the mixture follows a somewhat smooth and even combustion. A knock, when allowed to persist, reduces the effectiveness of engine bearings, and by doing so is death for a motor.\r\n\r\nAnd NOW you say, well.. My car takes 87 Octane fine, but my neighbor''s fancy lexus says Premium(92/93 here in WA) Only! Pardon me if you''re the one who''s car takes Premium, it''s just that I associate with the previous example better, if you catch my drift. Higher performance engines utilize a principle in piston motors called ''<a title="Timing" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignition_timing">Timing</a> advance''. Timing advance is a means of advancing when the spark plugs fire in relation to the position of the piston. I could talk for hours about how this happens, but this advance has a direct correlation to low-mid RPM band power. But the relationship between timing advance isn''t an indefinite linear relationship, and somewhere we hit a wall. This is where knock comes in. Again, in a way I can''t describe briefly, low octane fuel is more likely to elicit knock under timing advance than higher octane fuel is, hence why Car A takes 87 and car B takes 92.\r\n\r\nSo all the way back to instant advantage numero uno. You now understand that raising the octane of the fuel allows us to run more timing advance, and therefore get more power from the same amount of fuel. Short and sweet.\r\n\r\nOnto the second. We''re all familiar why a dog pants: because he/she is warm, and that the dissipated moisture coming out of their mouths is an excellent way to sink heat out of their bodies! Water vapor is an insanely good conductor of heat as most athletes sitting in front of a misting fan can attest to. The 50% of water in the injection mixture does just that. Due to the somewhere between 100 and 200 PSI of pressure in the lines and the small injector orifice, the mix comes out of the injector as atomized particles. As the water particles pass through the cylinder, they wick heat away and out the exhaust. So second advantage, lower Exhaust Gas Temperatures(EGT''s), which is always good!\r\n\r\nAnd for our long term advantage. Some of you have inevitably seen gas/car care commercials portraying this demon that is carbon building up on your pistons and valves, and how damaging it is over time. While I''m not prone to believe such claims, when you take an engine block''s top end off (down to the pistons), you''re greeted with a horror scene of blackened parts, and if you like shiny things, take a very long time to clean it. We''ve already mentioned the water''s advantage, BUT that wasn''t all, because water turns to steam when heated, right? Steam cleaning? YEAH! The water mixture, over time actually leads to cleaner pistons and exhaust valves! While I don''t have picture evidence, I shall provide the next time I tear down my engine block.\r\n\r\nOkay, so we''re clear on why this is good... Well apart from having one more tank that can get empty, an entire delivery control system, and another plumbing system in the car... Now is to what I mean by ''Preparing the system''. How I have it done, there is a controller that interfaces with a low tank sensor, flow sensor, the ground of a motor, a vacuum line, and the turbocharger''s wastegate solenoid. How this all works together i can explain in pseudo:\r\n<code>\r\nstartPSI=7; // Start injecting when the vacuum line reads 7PSI\r\nfullPSI=22; // Have the system running 100% when the line reads 22PSI;\r\nwhile(carIsRunning){\r\nif(The tank isn''t low &amp;&amp; SystemIsGood){ // the fuel isn''t low\r\nif(currentPSI &gt; startPSI){\r\npump.setPercent((currentPSI-startPSI)/fullPSI);//increase the pump''s duty cycle linearly   as the PSI rises to fullPSI\r\n}\r\nif(Flow sensor''s reading is lower than it''s estimate based on the pump''s duty cycle){\r\nSystemIsGood=false; // Shut down injection, something is wrong.\r\n}\r\n}else{\r\nturboSolenoidWire.set(HIGH);// Trigger a relay to cut voltage to the wastegate solenoid. This prevents the turbo from building boost that, occurring without methanol injection, could be catastrophic.\r\n}\r\n}</code>\r\n\r\nSo this all works nicely. So essentially what I''m manipulating is this start and end PSI, and in return can read the duty cycle of the pump and if the system has encountered some error. So really Tearing everything down served the purpose of running wires to create an <a title="I2C" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I%C2%B2C">I2C</a> BUS to interface with this module from the main controller! Woohoo!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOh and for the curmudgeonny tuner types, I re-tuned and adjusted both my timing advance AND target AFR maps for methanol injection.', 'Methanol Injection System ''Prepared''', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'methanol-injection-system-prepared', '', '', '2012-10-31 07:25:46', '2012-10-31 07:25:46', '', 0, 'http://www.oneseventyfour.com/?p=98', 0, 'post', '', 0),
